                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13187084" author="rgauss" created="Mon, 16 Jan 2012 19:01:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch to add support for parsing of dates with no time component.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13189888" author="gagravarr" created="Fri, 20 Jan 2012 16:46:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Do we want to set a timezone on these? For a date with no time, when turning it into a Java date (which does have a time component), I think it might be better to have it as Midnight UTC rather than Midnight local time (which is what we&apos;d otherwise get). I think Midnight UTC is likely to make more sense&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also, we&apos;ll likely want to support the more normal yyyy-mm-dd, as well as the image style yyyy:mm:dd in the patch&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13189895" author="rgauss" created="Fri, 20 Jan 2012 16:52:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Setting to midnight UTC after parsing sounds fine to me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;yyyy-mm-dd looks good too.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13189897" author="jukkaz" created="Fri, 20 Jan 2012 16:53:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;FWIW, I&apos;ve found it most reliable to convert a date with no time component to noon UTC of that day when a Java date is needed. Then it&apos;ll most likely fall within the correct day regardless of the local timezone.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13189905" author="rgauss" created="Fri, 20 Jan 2012 17:02:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Good point, noon sounds better.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13189908" author="gagravarr" created="Fri, 20 Jan 2012 17:07:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Initial support and tests for the two formats added in r1234003. In r1234004 I&apos;ve changed it to be noon UTC as suggested, should be fine for almost everyone (except somewhere like Samoa...)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
